# Obsidian Graph Analysis Plugin - Project Rules

## Code Organization
- TypeScript code for the plugin interface lives in `/src`
- Rust code for WebAssembly compilation lives in `/graph-analysis-wasm`
- Built files are generated in `/dist`

## Coding Standards
- Use TypeScript interfaces for data structures shared between components
- Document complex graph theory algorithms with comments explaining their purpose
- Follow Obsidian plugin conventions for UI components
- Use meaningful variable names that reflect graph theory concepts

## Architecture Patterns
- The main plugin class should handle initialization and command registration
- UI components should be separated from analysis logic
- WebAssembly interfaces should minimize data transfer between TypeScript and Rust
- Settings should validate and sanitize user input

## Feature Implementation Guide
- New centrality algorithms should be implemented in Rust when possible
- Each algorithm needs both an implementation and a UI component to display results
- All user-facing text should be clear and explain graph theory concepts simply
- Performance testing is required for algorithms on large graphs

## Workflow
- Build both TypeScript and Rust components before testing
- Run `npm run build` to build the full plugin
- Test in a development vault with varied note structures
- Branch naming should follow pattern: `feature/`, `fix/`, or `refactor/`

## Performance Considerations
- Minimize data transfer between TypeScript and Rust
- Consider memory usage when dealing with large graphs
- Implement fallback mechanisms for WebAssembly failures
- Profile performance on vaults of different sizes


# Project Rules and Patterns

## Migration Guidelines
1. Maintain exact calculation accuracy during migration
2. Implement and test one centrality metric at a time
3. Keep parallel implementations until verification is complete
4. Remove petgraph only after all tests pass

## Code Patterns
1. Centrality calculations should be modular and independently testable
2. Maintain clear separation between graph processing and plugin integration
3. Use type-safe interfaces for all graph operations
4. Include test cases for each centrality metric

## Project Workflow
1. Implement new functionality in parallel with existing code
2. Verify results against current implementation
3. Only remove old code after thorough testing
4. Document all significant changes

## Testing Requirements
1. Each centrality metric must have unit tests
2. Compare results between petgraph and rustnetworkx-core implementations
3. Performance benchmarks must be maintained or improved
4. Integration tests must pass before removing petgraph

## Documentation Standards
1. Clear comments for all centrality calculation functions
2. Updated API documentation reflecting library changes
3. Migration notes in changelog
4. Performance comparison documentation